{
  "answer": "**In Manusmṛti Chapter 8, the text addresses penalties for physical assault in verses 279–280 (and surrounding verses), with specific rules based on caste hierarchy.**\n\nA \"low-born man\" (typically a Shūdra or lower-caste individual) who injures a \"superior\" (higher-caste individual, such as a Brahmin) with a particular limb **shall have that very limb cut off**.[^1]\n\nThis is elaborated as follows: **one who raises a hand or stick deserves to have the hand cut off; one who strikes with the foot deserves to have the foot cut off**.[^2]\n\nThe broader context in Chapter 8 covers judicial penalties (*daṇḍa*) for assault (*prahāsa*), emphasizing retribution matching the offense and limb used, especially across castes (e.g., a low-born person sitting on a superior's seat warrants branding or buttock amputation).[^3] No exact phrase \"non-Brahmin who strikes a Brahmin\" appears, but \"low-born injuring superior\" directly applies, as Brahmins are the highest *varṇa* and non-Brahmins (*Kṣatriya*, *Vaiśya*, or *Shūdra*) are lower.\n\nThis is the precise rule from the corpus; other Dharmashāstras may vary, but Manusmṛti specifies limb amputation here.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-526528).\n[^2]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-c0dabc).\n[^3]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-a209b7).",
